etymologies: late Middle English; earliest use found in Cursor Mundi: a Northumbrian poem of the 14th century. Origin uncertain. Perhaps from early Scandinavian, perhaps showing a blend with wrinkle. Compare later ruckle. Perhaps compare also Middle Dutch (rare) wronckelen to twist, to wind, and the related noun wronckel
late Middle English; earliest use found in The Prick of Conscience. Probably from runkle

definitions: To wrinkle, rumple; (in later use also, of fabric, clothing, etc.) to ruck up.

notes.text: Apparently largely restricted to Scottish use between the 18th and early 20th centuries.
